ATTENTION WOODSTOCK 1 FRIDAY RIDERS!

Hello Woodstock 1 Families,

There will be a delay with the Woodstock 1 bus tomorrow morning (9/18). The bus will be delayed tomorrow by roughly 25 minutes. Another bus will be running its regular route and will then begin the W1 route. Please note, Butler Bus is estimating at least a 25 minute delay for these students.

In the afternoon, students will take the Woodstock 2 bus home tomorrow afternoon. If they are going to the Rainbow Playschool they will take the Pomfret bus tomorrow afternoon.

We apologize for any inconvenience!

If you have not completed our transportation survey yet, please take a minute to complete this quick survey. This data will be used to determine ridership for the upcoming school year. Please note, this survey needs to be completed in order to guarantee your child an assigned seat on the bus for this year. If your child rides in only the AM or PM, please complete this survey as we will treat your child as if they are a rider during both (they will be assigned a seat). If you believe you have already completed the survey and are unsure, please feel free to reach out or complete the survey again. Thank you for your time and support during this process.

https://forms.gle/CvqoHRGftSd8icVbA

https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLUsT1--vbZN1EIdVoi_Icpx1tXtAPOI9X

"It's not perfect, but it's beautiful." This has become one of our mantas in recent months. Year after year we look forward to our graduation events that bring us together as a learning community to honor and celebrate each year's graduating class. Typically at our ceremony on the beautiful green lawn along the banks of the Ottauquechee river, we're silent and transfixed on the speeches, music and Speakchorus. Presenting these as a playlist on YouTube doesn't nearly convey the same feelings and emotions as the live experience, but our students and administrators have been working hard to present their parting words in a thoughtful and meaningful manner. Take the time to listen to and enjoy these powerful speeches from our student leaders, faculty advisors and administrators.

Hartford Area Career and Technology Center, HACTC
June 3 at 9:35 AM ·

Congratulations to the following students who won the Maynard Maville Award!

Maynard Maville Award - This award is given in memory of Maynard Maville a long time staff member of the HACTC who passed away in February 2009. Qualities exhibited by the student receiving this award include; patient, caring, looks out for others, perseverance, trustworthy, respectful, sense of humor and has strong convictions.

Level II Maynard Maville Award Winners

Automotive Technology - Kylee Peck
Building Trades - Brent Potter
Business Administration - Eli Milligan
Career Technology Explorations A.M. - Noah Cook
Collision Repair and Refinishing - Ryan Reed
Computer Science - Kate Henggeler
Cosmetology - Charlotte Caron
Culinary Arts -Lilianna Eggleston
Design, Illustration, Media Arts - Tori Ross
Health Sciences - Nicole Harrington
Education Sciences Teaching & Learning- Jessica Marshall
Education Sciences Coaching & Leading-Paige Kleefisch
Industrial Mechanics and Welding -Carter Putnam
Natural Resources - Brock Evans
Introduction to Engineering Design - Adara Greenstein

post_text:
Yoh Theater presents...."She Kills Monsters" - Friday, June 5th @ 7 pm. (via Zoom)
Yoh Theatre Players will present their last show of the 2019-2020 season on Friday, June 5th at 7pm in a webinar format. Come and explore the world of Dungeons and Dragons with a recorded version of their work, including animation and voice-over, acting through zoom, sounds effects, costumes (from the shoulders up), hand-drawn maps, hand-made miniatures, and shadow-puppetry.

This presentation, with a TV-PG14 rating, contains coarse language, some suggestive dialogue, some sexual situations, and moderate violence.

Run time is 75 minutes, followed by a 20-minute Q&A with the actors. Save the date and invitations will follow.
Zoom link will appear on wuhsms.org and on FB.

post_text: The annual spring art show is always a beautiful showcase of student creativity, precision, passion, and hard work. It's a highlight and celebration that we as a school community look forward to every May. Due to the current Covid-19 pandemic and the "shelter in place" orders, we were sad to have to cancel this year's show and many other celebrations of learning that mark the end of each year on our school campus. But sometimes unfortunate circumstances cause us to look for and create new opportunities. Please visit our “Pop-Up” Mini Art Show in downtown Woodstock Village in the Morgan Block space next to the Woodstock Post Office. The majority of these pieces represent the beautiful work of our 12th-grade Advanced Placement Studio Art students plus several additional senior advanced art students. Works will be on display through Sunday, June 14th. Thank you to Bob Crowe (Dr. Coburn's Tonic) and Beth Finlayson (Woodstock Chamber of Commerce) for your support and helping to make this event happen.

post_text:
Celebrating #40DaysofWUHSMSSeniors #Day22

Meet Alice Sperber:
Extracurricular Activities: Soccer, Alpine, Track and Field, Student Council (President - 12), NHS.
Favorite WUHSMS Memory: My junior year we had a strong soccer team, but at the beginning of the season we didn’t realize how strong. We had a winning record and ended up winning the Marble Valley League. In that same season I scored my first and only varsity goal against Hartford and it was really fulfilling because I have always played defense. Coming off of a great soccer season I transitioned into ski racing pretty quickly. We had a pretty good season with a deep roster too. Going into states we were confident in our ability to perform and we ended up winning states and I also made the eastern team to represent Vermont at the Eastern High School Championships along with two others from Woodstock.
Plans after WUHSMS: University of Vermont Majoring in Biology.

Congratulations, Alice!

#WeAREWoodstock & #WeAREinThisTOGETHER

Celebrating #40DaysofWUHSMSSeniors #Day19

Meet Sam Powers:
Extracurricular Activities: Cross-Country Running, Cross-Country Skiing, Tennis, Math Team, Scholar's Bowl, Theatre
Zack's Place Snowshoeing, Joshin' with Ms. Piccoli, Culture Club
Favorite WUHSMS Memory: Janet North came up to me in the library and asked if I would help present about the Ottauquechee Health Foundation's fundraising efforts. I said yes and she then proceeded to hand me a manila envelope. Inside said envelope was a one-piece swimsuit. She thought it would be hilarious if I presented about their Polar Plunge event in full swimming regalia. I agreed and, the following week, I presented in front of the entire school as a scuba individual. I like this memory, not only because of Janet North's trust in my ability to be goofy, but also because I looked pretty good in that one-piece and, isn't that what's really important?

We Are Woodstock

This page is dedicated to the class of 2020. Stay Home, Stay Safe has led to missing milestones and recognition of their achievements. School is closed, and they have had to sacrifice traditions and celebrations.

The senior parents and the Windsor Central community have come together to support them and help them celebrate their final weeks and months before they leave for their final destinations.

Please note this announcement was just made by the VPA regarding Spring Sports season:

It is with great regret that the Vermont Principals' Association and its Activities Standards Committee announce the cancellation of the 2020 spring sports season.

Given the Governor's executive order "Stay Home Stay Safe" still extending at least through May 1Sth, and with no known expectation to return to in-person school for the 2019-2A school year, the difficult decision to cancel the 2020 spring sports season has been made.

post_text: Heads up Woodstock students who applied to the HACTC for next year.
shared_text:
Hartford Area Career and Technology Center, HACTC
April 7 at 7:57 AM ·

Dear HACTC Community,

Our intention every year is to try and notify students by the Friday before April Vacation if they have been admitted into the HACTC for the next school year. However, this year, due to a lot of variables related to the school building being closed and the staff working remotely, we are going to be about two weeks later than our intention.

If you know of a student that has applied for admission into the HACTC for the 20-21 school year, could you please pass along the above information? The sending school principals and school counselors have all been notified but we do not have a way to collectively notify the applicants.

Thank you for any assistance that you can provide and getting this message out.

Respectfully,

H
Proud Director
HACTC

A Message from College Board - Free SAT prep to help students through an uncertain time:

Over the last several weeks so much has changed, and we recognize that many students are experiencing a major disruption to their educational plans and daily lives. As we adjust to this new normal together, we want students to have the option to continue their test prep for free in a healthy, safe environment.

Right now, we’re offering a free month of SAT On Demand, which helps students master the exam in a little as 30 minutes a day. We also have free live lessons for the AP exams including World History, U.S. History, and Biology. There’s a lot more in our full resource hub—including free ACT prep. We hope it helps students feel a little less stressed during this uncertain time.

https://www.kaptest.com/sat/free/sat-on-demand-trial

https://www.youtube.com/user/KaplanSATACT/videos

post_text:
A message from Marcia Bender -

"We have cancelled our show (As You Like It) this weekend, due to the Coronavirus. We are all disappointed not to perform, but understand the importance of these cautionary measures.

Our students did a dress rehearsal this evening, after many tears, and the energy, love for theatre, and feeling of community and excitement was astounding. They performed beautifully and left feeling successful and happy.

Thanks to everyone making tough decisions about school life. We at Yoh appreciate all the support we get from administration and teachers and staff. Thank you all."

post_text: We are so incredibly proud of our amazing Alumni, Molly Thompson! Keep sharing your amazing words of wisdom! You Are Woodstock!
shared_text:
Oxbow High School
January 9 at 11:25 AM ·

Yesterday we had a callback assembly where guest speaker Molly Thompson came in to speak to students about empathy and kindness. Molly went to Hartland Elementary school and then Woodstock High School, she is now currently at Saint Michael’s College in Colchester, VT where she is studying to become a college professor. Molly was born with Pfeiffer Syndrome, a disorder characterized by the prefusion of certain skull bones, along with a variety of other health issues. She talked to students about what it is like to have a disability and persevere. Molly is working to advocate for those who are different or have disabilities. She talked to the students about being kind, asking appropriate questions and be respectful to those who are different. Thank you Molly for coming to OHS and telling your story.

post_text: The 9th graders participated in the 3 Squares Vermont food challenge this past week. In Wellness I, students were challenged to plan a weeks worth of food off of $36. This is the amount of money a person in Vermont receives for food assistance. In addition to planning and budgeting, students analyzed the nutrients of the food. 9th graders traveled to Hannaford Grocery Store in West Lebanon to purchase their items and then had the opportunity to donate their food to the The Haven, a local food shelf. At The Haven, students learned about food insecurity and homelessness. Next week students will reflect on their experiences in Modern World class and discuss connections to the Hungry Planet project which chronicles what people around the world consume and spend per week. This project will culminate with students taking action by investigating ways to reduce food insecurity.

Woodstock Interact Club has some amazing news to share!

The WUHS Interact club has taken on the responsibility of keeping the WUHSMS lost-and-found organized and efficient. This webpage is our way of communicating what items we have found and when, so you can look for your things and claim them. Because Interact would like to give back to our community as well as keep our school neat, we will periodically be donating Lost and Found items to our local Listen and Haven centers. Items will be kept for one month before they are donated. If you see something of yours on this page, please promptly pick it up, send your student to pick it up, or contact us to arrange something else.

The date below the image indicates the date by which we will be donating your item -- NOT the date which the item was found.

https://sites.google.com/view/wuhsinteract/lost-found?authuser=0

October 22, 2019 at 2:28 PM ·

Why are the leaves changing color?
It’s due to decreasing sunlight and that causes the green chlorophyll to disappear giving way to the red pigment.🍁 It’s the same effect of why maples, aspen and other deciduous tree leaves change color at this time of year.🍂 Poinsettia Sale begins in mid November. $7.00 each or 3 for $20.00 (Video📽 by Orion Conger)

post_text: Don't forget to join our HACTC Seniors as they are presented with certificates of completion at the HACTC Senior Awards Night on May 21st @6:30pm.
shared_text:
Hartford Area Career and Technology Center, HACTC
May 15, 2019 at 8:40 AM ·

SAVE THE DATE: May 21st @ 6:30

The Senior Awards Night for the Hartford Area Career and Technology Center (HACTC) will be on May 21st at the Lebanon Opera House.

The evening will begin at 6:30 and all students who are currently seniors at the HACTC are invited and expected to attend, even those seniors that are in Level I programs this year or have completed a semester-long program as a senior.

Scholarships and awards will be presented to some students but all students will be recognized by receiving a certificate of completion on stage from their instructor.

It is a wonderful evening and the HACTC Team looks forward to seeing you there!

#thisiswhatcelebrationlookslike #thisiswhatlearninglookslike

On Wednesday, 4/24/2019, La Société Honoraire (French Honors Society) and La sociedad honoraria hispánica (Spanish Honors Society) inducted 14 members and 7 members respectively. post_text: We had 12 amazing students bring 10 projects to the Vermont State Science, Math, Technology, Engineering and Math Fair today. It was the culmination of months of work that they began in September. A few were independent studies (thank you C3) but most chose to take on this challenge outside of scheduled class time. They earned a total of 14 awards including a silver medal for Lili Sorrentino, gold medals for Momo Biele and Emily Dean and another invitation to the International Science and Engineering Fair for Emily Dean. She will be going to Phoenix in May to compete. Many students were also offered scholarships to attend the National Academy of Sciences to further hone their scientific research skills.

Toby Borzekowski, was a National Qualifier from this weekends Speech and Debate Tournament. Toby and Gordon Ladd, advisor, will be traveling to Dallas in June for the National Speech and Debate Association National Tournament. Also, for the first time ever, all of the members of the Woodstock Forensics Team qualified for the Final Round. Eric Dorfman, Alison Libley, Haley Symonds, and Alivia Salls all placed in the top five in their respective categories. Please congratulate all of our team members! Toby Borzekowski, Nina Borzekowski, Alivia Salls, Haley Symonds, Julia Kowalski, Erik Dorfman, and Riley Chynoweth

Erik Dorfman placed second in International Extemp, Alivia Salls and Haley Symonds placed 4th in Duo Drama and Alison Libley placed 5th in Congress.

*Picture of all National Qualifiers from the WUHS Tournament this weekend.*

post_text:
On March 9, Soulfully Good Café will be hosting an art sale to benefit the WUHS AP Art class. The works of art are original creations by students taking Advanced Placement and independent study art classes. This very talented group of students have produced a variety of works including landscapes, nature scenes and cubist-inspired pieces using acrylic and watercolor paints. They are on small canvases and will be very reasonably priced. All proceeds are going towards their museum field trip to New York City where they will be exploring the collections of The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Museum of Modern Art. A highlight of the trip will be the gallery talks the students will be giving for their classmates at the museums.
Please join the students at Soulfully Good Café at 67 Central Street in Woodstock on March 9 from 3:00-4:00pm to meet the artists, view and purchase the paintings and enjoy a late lunch. The works of art will be on view and available for purchase through March 24.

post_text: Just prior to the holiday break, AP Art students did a Bob Ross painting lesson in real time. Students and their teachers worked quickly to gather their pigments and brushes and painted a mountainous landscape scene including clusters of trees painted rapidly with fan brushes. In the lesson Ross reminds his students, " There's nothing wrong with having a tree as a friend." Several students familiar with Bob Ross' style and technique reminded their classmates who thought they made a mistake that, as Bob Ross says, "We don't make mistakes, just happy little accidents." It was a great activity that resulted in some very beautiful landscape paintings in approximately thirty minutes!

post_text: A great day of activism and civic engagement! 38 students in grades 9-12 marched and rallied in Montpelier as part of the Youth Rally For The Planet. It's a climate change rally for youth organized by youth. They marched, listened to student speakers, discussed climate change with lawmakers and visited many information booths and tables.

post_text: The Sweetest Season! Advanced Agriculture students have put in 29 taps at the nearby King Farm, owned by the Vermont Land Trust. Students manage every aspect of the maple sugaring process, from start to finish. We just finished our first batch of the year-just over a half-gallon of Delicate grade syrup.

The Phys Ed program is going strong at WUHSMS.

post_text: Kudos to Susan Piccoli and members of the Culture Club. This year, they'restudying recent immigrant and refugee cultures. In preparation for their trip to NYC to see Ai Weiwei’s installation Good Fences Make Good Neighbors, they went to see his documentary Human Flow which is about the international refugee crisis at the Hopkins Center to help frame our examination of his installations of fences in New York City.

post_text: Sometimes you just have to stop what you're doing, take a break and celebrate a little. During Winter Carnival, we take a short break in the middle of the school year and our hallways become bowling alleys, our athletic fields turn into sledding hills and fat bike courses. We relax, appreciate each other, eat terrific pizza and cotton candy and press the reset button. Thanks to our student council, Sra. Bristow, Madam Anderson and all involved in organizing the afternoon!.

post_text: Our physics students have spent the last week working with NuVu associate Dustin Brugmann to develop electricity-free kitchen gadgets. The gadgets could be used in disaster-relief zones or for camping or, perhaps, just for whimsical purposes. Students have brainstormed multiple ideas, drawn them from different perspectives, and crafted 3D versions out of cardboard! Next week, they'll spiral through the design process, creating digitized drawings that can drive laser cutters and 3D printers.

post_text: WUHS participated in this year's Women Can Do event at Vemont Technical College. Women Can Do is a one-day career immersion experience for 9-12th grade girls from across Vermont. It features dozens of hands-on workshops and action stations highlighting careers in the skilled trades and STEM (science, technology, engineering, and math) fields. Kudos to Hannah Leland for organizing the trip.
